<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-172-056  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 172 056.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC-Computing  March 1990 v3 n3 p60(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Hey, comrade, want some software? (Soviet computer club enlistingaid from hardware and software vendors)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Taylor, Wendy.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Soviet UnionTechnology transferHardware VendorsSoftware PublishersInternational Trade.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Hey, Comrade, Want Some Software? As the Iron Curtain tumbles, Sovietuniversities and industries are looking to the West for computer technology.andO;The Moscow-based International Computer Club (ICC; Proyezd Serova 4, Moscow,USSR 101813), in fact, is enlisting the help of hardware and softwarecompanies abroad in the hopes of making computing easier and more accessiblein the USSR.andM;In exchange for hardware, software, and other kinds of monetary and technicalsupport, the nongovernmental ICC helps companies cultivate customers fortheir products by providing market research and product exposure.andP;  The group,whose members come from a variety of businesses seeking access to products onthe international market, has attracted high-tech firms from Great Britain,Italy, Bulgaria, France, Luxembourg, Hungary, West Germany, Singapore, andthe United States.andP;  Among the U.S.andP;  participants is California's BorlandInternational.andP;  &quot;Turbo Pascal and Paradox have become standards in the SovietUnion,&quot; says Borland vice president of corporate affairs Bob Kohn.andP;  &quot;We areworking with ICC to set up a Borland user group.&quot;andM;Borland's motives aren't entirely philanthropic.andP;  Kohn concedes that much ofthe Borland software being used in the USSR is unauthorized.andP;  &quot;But pastinfringement is not at issue,&quot; he says.andP;  Indeed, if Borland can attract adedicated following, it will reap the benefits in profits later on.andO;</TEXT></DOC>